Last September/October, I almost went homeless.

Now, I've paid of $10k in debt (still got $35k left).  My goal was initially to retire to write full time by 40, but now my goal is to be debt-free before I turn 41.  Then keep saving 25% of my income so I can retire to write.

full_text: Jesus, this went long.  Sorry.  The point being, I want to maintain my progress.  If I get 1 person who loves my novel, that's enough to keep writing.  Because I understand now how fragile that progress is.  How easy it is to give up without even knowing you're doing it.

And I've learned how to nurture the flame in my own long-term projects.  https://t.co/z3Jm9z1LYw has been a fantastic help with that, for my instinct when I hit the wall is to find something that gives me the spark.  

Now, I bring the spark within me.

full_text: This year, I've really worked hard on both.  "Joining" (I'm not a member) the @FurWritersGuild helped me both find new people and be part of a community again, as well as get my writing out there with things like Voice of Dog.

full_text:
Why did I fail?  Two big reasons: 1. I was always searching for the inspiration that comes a new project.  A novel has that‚Äîand then 1000 more hours of slog.

2. I needed a community to talk to.  I had tried a couple times, post LJ, but always failed to find one right for me.

I needed a community to talk to.  I had tried a couple times, post LJ, but always failed to find one right for me.'

full_text:
But, in the thing I've wanted since grade 2, I had failed utterly.  I was entering middle age, and I had never finished a novel.  Never published a short story outside of some university zines.

And while I had saved money to retire early and write, that got taken away from me.
full_text(utf-8): b"But, in the thing I've wanted since grade 2, I had failed utterly.  I was entering middle age, and I had never finished a novel.  Never published a short story outside of some university zines.\n\nAnd while I had saved money to retire early and write, that got taken away from me."

full_text: Toward the end of last year, I did a lot of introspection.  I generally am successful at life: I have partners who support me and whom I love; I have a job that's meaningful and pays enough for me to have a house I'm proud of; I have passion in rugby and lifting.

full_text: A responsible person, when they make a mistake, does not feel overwhelming guilt.  They feel a need to correct the mistake and ensure it does not happen again.
full_text(utf-8): b'A responsible person, when they make a mistake, does not feel overwhelming guilt.  They feel a need to correct the mistake and ensure it does not happen again.'

full_text: Feeling guilt can spur responsibility sometimes, but it can also be a shield against taking responsibility.  Demonstrating guilt can make others believe it couldn't have been avoided--when the person won't change.  Feeling too much guilt can also paralyse a person.
full_text(utf-8): b"Feeling guilt can spur responsibility sometimes, but it can also be a shield against taking responsibility.  Demonstrating guilt can make others believe it couldn't have been avoided--when the person won't change.  Feeling too much guilt can also paralyse a person."

full_text:
Do not confuse feeling bad with taking responsibility.

You can feel bad for a mistake, beat yourself up, yet make no changes and continue to make the same mistake.

Or you can accept that it was just a mistake, then see how the situation can be fixed and what to do differently.

b'Do not confuse feeling bad with taking responsibility.
